The <b>Ruddy Crake</b> (<i>Laterallus ruber</i>) is a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">bird</a> in the rail family, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rallidae" title="Rallidae">Rallidae</a>. It is a small crake, 14-16.5&nbsp;cm in length. It is mostly bright chestnut in colour with a paler chin and belly, blackish crown and dark grey ear-coverts. The <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beak" title="Beak">bill</a> is black, the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iris_(anatomy)" title="Iris (anatomy)">iris</a> is red and the legs and feet are olive-green.
The bird occurs from <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a> south to north-west <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Costa_Rica" title="Costa Rica">Costa Rica</a>. It is found in freshwater habitats such as marshes, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reedbed" title="Reedbed" class="mw-redirect">reedbeds</a>, damp fields and ditches.
